# Metadata and SEO

Next.js gives you two ways to produce per-route `<head>` content: static `export const metadata` and dynamic `generateMetadata`. Plus file-convention generators for robots / sitemap / manifest / OG images. This rule covers the shape, the v16-specific gotchas, and the patterns LLMs get wrong.

## Static `metadata` export

The simplest form. Use when the metadata is the same for every request to this route.

```typescript
// app/about/page.tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'About',
  description: 'About this site',
  openGraph: {
    title: 'About',
    description: 'About this site',
    images: ['/about-og.png'],
  },
};

export default function AboutPage() {
  return <h1>About</h1>;
}
```

## Dynamic `generateMetadata`

Use when metadata depends on `params`, `searchParams`, or fetched data.

### v16: both `params` and `searchParams` are async

```typescript
// BAD - v15 shape, TypeError in v16
export async function generateMetadata(
  { params }: { params: { slug: string } }
): Promise<Metadata> {
  const post = await getPost(params.slug);
  return { title: post.title };
}

// CORRECT - v16
import type { Metadata, ResolvingMetadata } from 'next';

type Props = {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
  searchParams: Promise<{ [key: string]: string | string[] | undefined }>;
};

export async function generateMetadata(
  { params, searchParams }: Props,
  parent: ResolvingMetadata
): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await getPost(slug);

  // Compose with parent metadata (e.g. inherit openGraph defaults)
  const parentOg = (await parent).openGraph ?? {};
  const parentImages = parentOg.images ?? [];

  return {
    title: post.title,
    description: post.excerpt,
    openGraph: {
      ...parentOg,
      title: post.title,
      description: post.excerpt,
      images: [post.coverImage, ...(Array.isArray(parentImages) ? parentImages : [parentImages])],
    },
  };
}
```

`generateMetadata` runs at request time. The result is merged with any parent layout's `metadata` exports - parent fields are inherited unless this segment overrides them.

## `title.template` for app-wide title patterns

A root layout can declare a title template; every child page only sets its own slug.

```typescript
// app/layout.tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: {
    default: 'My App',          // used if a child has no title
    template: '%s | My App',    // %s is replaced with the child's title
  },
  description: 'Default description',
};

// app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx
export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await getPost(slug);
  return { title: post.title }; // becomes "Post Title | My App"
}
```

`title.absolute` opts out of the template for one page:

```typescript
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: { absolute: 'Custom Page Title' }, // template is ignored
};
```

## `openGraph` and `twitter`

```typescript
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'My Page',
  openGraph: {
    title: 'My Page',
    description: 'Description for social cards',
    url: 'https://example.com/my-page',
    siteName: 'My App',
    images: [
      { url: '/og.png', width: 1200, height: 630, alt: 'My Page' },
    ],
    locale: 'en_US',
    type: 'website',
  },
  twitter: {
    card: 'summary_large_image',
    title: 'My Page',
    description: 'Description for social cards',
    images: ['/og.png'],
    creator: '@myhandle',
  },
};
```

When `twitter` is omitted, the Twitter crawler falls back to `openGraph`. You only need explicit `twitter` for divergent card content.

## `metadataBase` for canonical URL resolution

Relative URLs (`/og.png`, `/about`) in metadata need a base. Set `metadataBase` once at the root layout.

```typescript
// BAD - no metadataBase, every relative URL emits a warning
// app/layout.tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'My App',
  openGraph: {
    images: ['/og.png'], // "metadataBase property is not set" warning
  },
};

// CORRECT
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  metadataBase: new URL(
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3000'
  ),
  title: { default: 'My App', template: '%s | My App' },
  openGraph: {
    images: ['/og.png'], // resolved to https://example.com/og.png
  },
};
```

Set this in the root layout. Child segments inherit it.

## `robots.ts`

```typescript
// app/robots.ts
import type { MetadataRoute } from 'next';

export default function robots(): MetadataRoute.Robots {
  const base = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL ?? 'https://example.com';
  return {
    rules: [
      { userAgent: '*', allow: '/', disallow: ['/admin', '/api'] },
    ],
    sitemap: `${base}/sitemap.xml`,
  };
}
```

For staging / preview environments, return a "no index" rule:

```typescript
export default function robots(): MetadataRoute.Robots {
  if (process.env.VERCEL_ENV !== 'production') {
    return { rules: [{ userAgent: '*', disallow: '/' }] };
  }
  return { rules: [{ userAgent: '*', allow: '/' }], sitemap: '...' };
}
```

## `sitemap.ts`

```typescript
// app/sitemap.ts
import type { MetadataRoute } from 'next';
import { getAllPosts } from '@/lib/dal/posts';

export default async function sitemap(): Promise<MetadataRoute.Sitemap> {
  const base = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL ?? 'https://example.com';
  const posts = await getAllPosts();

  const staticRoutes: MetadataRoute.Sitemap = [
    { url: `${base}/`, lastModified: new Date('2026-01-01'), priority: 1.0 },
    { url: `${base}/about`, lastModified: new Date('2026-03-15'), priority: 0.8 },
  ];

  const postRoutes: MetadataRoute.Sitemap = posts.map(post => ({
    url: `${base}/blog/${post.slug}`,
    lastModified: post.updatedAt,
    priority: 0.6,
  }));

  return [...staticRoutes, ...postRoutes];
}
```

### Paginated sitemaps for >50K URLs

Sitemaps cap at 50K URLs / 50MB per Google's spec. Split into multiple sitemaps with `generateSitemaps`.

```typescript
// app/sitemap.ts
import type { MetadataRoute } from 'next';

export async function generateSitemaps(): Promise<{ id: number }[]> {
  // Compute how many shards you need based on your post count
  const total = await getPostCount();
  const shards = Math.ceil(total / 50_000);
  return Array.from({ length: shards }, (_, i) => ({ id: i }));
}

export default async function sitemap(
  { id }: { id: number }
): Promise<MetadataRoute.Sitemap> {
  const start = id * 50_000;
  const posts = await getPostsRange(start, start + 50_000);
  return posts.map(p => ({
    url: `https://example.com/blog/${p.slug}`,
    lastModified: p.updatedAt,
  }));
}
```

## `manifest.ts`

```typescript
// app/manifest.ts
import type { MetadataRoute } from 'next';

export default function manifest(): MetadataRoute.Manifest {
  return {
    name: 'My App',
    short_name: 'MyApp',
    description: 'Description',
    start_url: '/',
    display: 'standalone',
    background_color: '#ffffff',
    theme_color: '#0369A1',
    icons: [
      { src: '/icon-192.png', sizes: '192x192', type: 'image/png' },
      { src: '/icon-512.png', sizes: '512x512', type: 'image/png' },
    ],
  };
}
```

## Dynamic OG images with `next/og`

`opengraph-image.tsx`, `twitter-image.tsx`, `icon.tsx`, `apple-icon.tsx` are file conventions. Each is a React component that returns an `ImageResponse`.

```typescript
// app/blog/[slug]/opengraph-image.tsx
import { ImageResponse } from 'next/og';
import { getPost } from '@/lib/dal/posts';

export const size = { width: 1200, height: 630 };
export const contentType = 'image/png';

// v16: params is a Promise
export default async function OG({ params }: { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> }) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const post = await getPost(slug);

  return new ImageResponse(
    (
      <div
        style={{
          width: '100%',
          height: '100%',
          background: '#0F172A',
          color: '#F8FAFC',
          padding: 80,
          display: 'flex',
          flexDirection: 'column',
          justifyContent: 'center',
        }}
      >
        <h1 style={{ fontSize: 72, margin: 0 }}>{post.title}</h1>
        <p style={{ fontSize: 32, color: '#94A3B8' }}>{post.author.name}</p>
      </div>
    ),
    size
  );
}
```

### v16: `id` in `generateImageMetadata` is async

If you generate multiple OG images per route via `generateImageMetadata`, the callback receives `id` as a Promise (was a string in v15).

```typescript
// BAD - v15 shape
export default function OG({ id }: { id: string }) {
  return new ImageResponse(<div>{id}</div>, size);
}

// CORRECT - v16
export async function generateImageMetadata() {
  return [
    { id: 'card-light', size: { width: 1200, height: 630 }, contentType: 'image/png' },
    { id: 'card-dark', size: { width: 1200, height: 630 }, contentType: 'image/png' },
  ];
}

export default async function OG({
  params,
  id,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
  id: Promise<string>;
}) {
  const [{ slug }, variant] = await Promise.all([params, id]);
  const post = await getPost(slug);
  const isDark = variant === 'card-dark';

  return new ImageResponse(
    <div style={{ background: isDark ? '#0F172A' : '#F8FAFC' }}>{post.title}</div>,
    { width: 1200, height: 630 }
  );
}
```

### Runtime selection for `ImageResponse`

`ImageResponse` runs on the Edge runtime by default. Opt into Node.js when you need Node-only APIs (e.g. reading a file with `fs`).

```typescript
export const runtime = 'nodejs'; // default is 'edge'
```

### Tailwind utilities inside `ImageResponse` via `tw=`

`ImageResponse` uses Satori under the hood, which supports a subset of CSS. The `tw=` prop applies Tailwind-style utility classes via a converter.

```typescript
return new ImageResponse(
  (
    <div tw="flex flex-col items-center justify-center w-full h-full bg-slate-900 text-white">
      <h1 tw="text-7xl font-bold">{post.title}</h1>
      <p tw="text-3xl text-slate-400 mt-4">{post.author.name}</p>
    </div>
  ),
  size
);
```

Caveats:

- Not all Tailwind classes are supported (no animations, no transforms, no `gradient-to-*` shorthand).
- The font must be loaded explicitly if you want anything other than the Satori default. Pass `fonts` in the `ImageResponse` options.

### Don't hardcode URLs in OG images

```typescript
// BAD - hardcoded production URL, breaks on staging
<img src="https://example.com/logo.png" />

// CORRECT - read from env, fall back sensibly
const base = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3000';
<img src={`${base}/logo.png`} />
```

For relative URLs the file system has direct access to, `next/og` can also read from `public/` via `fs` (Node runtime only).

## `icon.tsx` and `apple-icon.tsx`

```typescript
// app/icon.tsx - generates the favicon
import { ImageResponse } from 'next/og';

export const size = { width: 32, height: 32 };
export const contentType = 'image/png';

export default function Icon() {
  return new ImageResponse(
    (
      <div style={{ background: '#0369A1', color: 'white', fontSize: 24, width: '100%', height: '100%', display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
        M
      </div>
    ),
    size
  );
}
```

`apple-icon.tsx` has the same shape, conventionally `180x180`.

## Common mistakes

- **Sync `params` destructure in `generateMetadata`.** v16 TypeError. `params` is a Promise.
- **Sync `searchParams` destructure.** Same fix.
- **Missing `metadataBase`.** Every relative URL emits a warning at build time. Set it once at the root layout.
- **Hardcoded URLs in OG images.** Breaks on staging / preview. Read from env.
- **No fallback `metadata.title`.** A child page without a title uses the template's `default`. Make sure both are set.
- **`lastModified: new Date()` in `sitemap.ts`.** Cache-busts every build, signals Google to re-crawl every URL pointlessly. Use the actual modification time of the underlying data.
- **Missing `robots: { index: false }` on staging.** Search engines index your preview deploys. Gate by `VERCEL_ENV` or similar.
- **Sync `id` in `generateImageMetadata` callbacks.** v16 made it async. Await it.
- **`ImageResponse` with `<img src="local.png">` on Edge runtime.** Edge can't read local files. Use Node runtime or fetch the image at build time and embed as base64.
- **Static `metadata` export plus `generateMetadata` in the same file.** Only one is allowed per route segment. Pick one.
- **OG image >5MB.** Twitter / Facebook reject. Keep dimensions at 1200x630 and the rendered PNG well under 1MB.
- **Tailwind class on `ImageResponse` that Satori doesn't support.** Silently ignored. Check the Satori CSS subset.
